# First, I plot the Elbow Curve in order to see how k influence the variation

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

within_cluster_variance = [] # initiate empty list with no data

# build models for range of ks from 2 to 20
for k in range(2, 20):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    within_cluster_variance.append(kmeans.inertia_)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.plot(range(2, 20), within_cluster_variance, marker='o')
plt.grid(True)
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Reduction in within cluster variation')

plt.title('Elbow curve')  #Choose k at elbow of plot as a general rule.  We want a small enough number of categories to 
                          # such that we can still learn something meaningful from them via exploration of our variables.
Out[6]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Elbow curve')

Wikipedia says: "In clustering, this means one should choose a number of clusters so that adding another cluster doesn't give much better modeling of the data." Through the above elbow chart, we can plot reduction within cluster variation for each k. From the plot we can see that, as the number of clusters (k) increases, reduction in the variation decreases.

I want to identify high & low quality of wine, I decide to check k=2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,12 to see how these k works. I want to get the k, which makes the quality value diverge the most.

To choose which k is the best for my unsupervised learning, I need to be certain that the purpose of my analysis is to segment these wine data using the quality feature. Therefore, I should check which k makes the wine quality most distinct.

However, looking at the number might be a little bit of difficult, so I draw a scatter plot to make it more convenient to see.

In [35]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3)
kmeans.fit(X)
y_kmeans = kmeans.predict(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
#plot original data colored by k-means clusters from model
plt.scatter(X.iloc[:, 0], X.iloc[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis',alpha=0.5)

centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_ # extract final centroids from each cluster
plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='black', s=250, alpha=0.99);

Answer for Question 1) K-means¶

--- I choose k = 3 because 1) it appears to make the wine quality most distinct from the numerical analysis and 2) the scatter plot appears to be nice and 3) There is a turn when k=3 in the elbow curve.¶

--- From the analysis above, we can see that the variables that cluster with higher values of wine quality includes: fixed acidity, citric, density, sulphates and alcohol. From the analysis above, we can see that the variables that cluster with lower values of wine quality includes: residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.¶

--- If I want to make good wines, according to the K-means model, I need to make sure it has high fixed acidity, citric, density, sulphates and alcohol. At the same time, I will need to lower residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.¶

Answer for Question 2) Hierarchical Cluster Analysis, K = 3 and Linkage = "complete"¶

--- From the analysis above, we can see that the variables that cluster with higher values of wine quality includes: fixed acidity, residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide and density. From the analysis above, we can see that the variables that cluster with lower values of wine quality includes: citric acid, chlorides and sulphates¶

--- If I want to make good wines, I need to make sure it has high fixed acidity, citric, density, sulphates and alcohol. At the same time, I will need to lower residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.¶

--- By comparing the scatter plots for the K-means model and the Hierarchical Cluster Analysis Model, as well as the feature analysis, I have to say that these two models are pretty different in predicting "good quality wines".¶

Optional Analysis - As I mention above, I fell "ward" linkage would be a better option, so I condcut the same analysis using "ward" linkage again here¶

Answer for Quesntion 3 - PCA¶

- From the plot above, we can see that around 43% of the variation in the data can be explained by the first two principal components.¶

- The first principal component places more positive weight on variable fixed acidity and places negative weights on variable pH. The second principal component places positive weight on variable total sulfur dioxide and negative weight on variables alcohol and quality.¶

- PCA is useful for decresing the dimension of a dataframe. In addition, principal components can be directly used as the features when doing supervised learninf. If we want to build a supervised learning model for wine price using the frist two principal components, we can certainly use the two principal components as the independent features to build supervised learning models.¶
